          <h2 id="smart-home">Smart Home Devices</h2>
          <p>Smart home devices reduce friction for guests, minimize key management headaches, and protect your property remotely. The core devices every Airbnb host should consider are locks, thermostats, and leak detectors.</p>

          <h3>Smart Locks</h3>
          <p>Smart locks eliminate the need for physical key handoffs, which is one of the most common sources of friction in self-managed rentals. Guests receive a unique access code before check-in that automatically expires after checkout. Most major PMS platforms integrate directly with smart locks, generating and sending codes as part of the automated booking workflow.</p>

          <p>For a detailed comparison of smart lock models and PMS integration compatibility, see our <a href="/blog/best-smart-locks-airbnb-check-in-2026">smart locks guide for Airbnb hosts</a>.</p>

          <h3>Smart Thermostats</h3>
          <p>Smart thermostats from Ecobee and Nest let you manage temperature remotely, set schedules around guest arrival and departure, and prevent guests from running extreme heating or cooling settings that spike your utility bills. Ecobee integrates with more smart home ecosystems and supports remote sensors for room-by-room temperature visibility. Setting a temperature range limit (for example, 16 to 26 degrees Celsius) protects your energy costs while keeping guests comfortable.</p>

          <h3>Water Leak Detectors</h3>
          <p>A single undetected water leak can cause tens of thousands of dollars in damage. Devices like Flo by Moen and Phyn monitor water flow and pressure, detecting unusual patterns that indicate leaks, burst pipes, or appliance failures. Flo by Moen can automatically shut off water supply when a leak is detected. At $100 to $500 for hardware, these devices represent some of the best risk-reduction value available for property protection.</p>

